article.description:
Shawn Marion had 32 points and 14 rebounds,
and the Phoenix Suns defeated the Los Angeles Clippers 97-94 Saturday night to snap a seven-game road losing streak.
article.headline: Marion collects 32 points, 14 rebounds
article.linkText: Marion buries Clippers, helps Suns end six-game skid
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Phoenix jumped on Los Angeles in the first quarter, then didn't panic when the Clippers threatened in the final 12 minutes.
Marbury

The Suns' poise earned them a 97-94 victory Saturday night that snapped a seven-game road losing streak. "If we have any chance of making the playoffs, this is where we have to start," said Stephon Marbury, who had 24 points and 11 assists for Phoenix, which had lost nine of 11. "The only way that we can go out and have something to play for is by putting in our minds that the playoffs are still reality," he said. The Clippers' playoff hopes took a jolt with the defeat that left them 2½ games behind Utah for the eighth and final Western Conference berth. "It was a tough loss, but the bottom line is that we play Utah two more times, so we're not going to get too down about this one," said Eric Piatkowski, who missed two desperation 3-pointers in the waning seconds that would've forced overtime. "We're not out of it by any means. If we play good ball from here on out, we'll be all right because who knows how Utah is going to finish out the season," he said. Shawn Marion led the Suns with 32 points and 14 rebounds despite pain from a lower back strain that forced him to sit out Thursday's loss to Detroit. "We needed this. We're trying to finish the season strong," he said. "That's what everyone's mentality is right now and that's what we've got to focus on." The Suns dominated in winning on the road for the first time since Feb. 21 at Memphis. They also ended a season-worst six-game losing skid. Except for the opening basket and a third-quarter tie, Phoenix led the entire game and withstood the Clippers' rally in the last 12 minutes. The Suns shot 46 percent in the first quarter and took a 26-13 lead. The Clippers were just 6-for-21 from the floor and had eight turnovers. "That first quarter really set the tone," Clippers forward Elton Brand said. "They came out and ran, which is what we expected, but we just didn't get back on defense." Piatkowski hit a 3-pointer with 8.5 seconds left to draw the Clippers to 95-94. Jeff McInnis was forced to foul Marbury, who made both free throws as Phoenix led 97-94. Piatkowski missed two 3-point attempts as time expired. "I still thought the ball was going to go in. It looked pretty good all the way there, but it barely missed," he said of his final attempt. "That was exactly the play we wanted. It was pretty much an open shot and I got a pretty good look at it, so you can't really complain too much about that." Quentin Richardson scored 20 points in reserve for the Clippers, who had won two in a row. McInnis added 18 points, Brand had 16 points and 14 rebounds, and Michael Olowokandi had 16 points. Olowokandi wasn't happy about sitting out 6½ minutes in the fourth quarter when the game was on the line. He came back with 3:16 remaining and the Clippers down by five points. "There's nothing I can do in three minutes. I don't know who the genius is who decided that," he said. "I was in a position where I could help the ballclub in crunch time." Los Angeles got within one early in the fourth quarter only to see the Suns push their lead back to six points on a 3-pointer by Dan Majerle and two free throws by Marion. "I had confidence that we were going to have a chance to win it in the end after we came back, but Dan Majerle really hurt us," Piatkowski said. "He came in and knocked some big 3s down, and that was the ballgame right there." The Clippers kept challenging, though, cutting the deficit to 90-88 on a free throw by McInnis with 1:01 remaining. Marion answered with a jumper, and after a timeout, Brand missed a hook shot and fouled. Marion made two free throws and the Suns led 94-88. McInnis hit a 3-pointer to draw the Clippers to 94-91 with 13 seconds left. Phoenix's Joe Johnson got fouled and made one of two free throws for a 95-91 lead. Piatkowski countered with the Clippers' third consecutive 3-pointer to trail 95-94, but he couldn't duplicate the feat on two tries to force overtime. The Clippers trailed by 13 points when they got back into the game midway through the third quarter. They outscored the Suns 14-2, including six points by Brand, to tie it at 64. Brand's tying basket came on a goaltending call against Marion. But Marion quickly made amends by hitting a runner. Majerle had a 3-pointer, and Jake Voskuhl made one of two free throws to put the Suns back in front, 70-66, going into the final 12 minutes. "We expended a lot of energy being down, and once you're down like that, everything has to be perfect," Brand said. "A few balls didn't bounce our way and a few layups didn't go in." Los Angeles trailed by 14 in the second quarter before outscoring Phoenix 13-6 to end the half trailing 49-40. Marion had 18 points in the first half -- one more than the Clippers' starting five. Game notes
The Suns won just their second road game under coach Frank Johnson, who took over Feb. 17 after Scott Skiles was fired. They are 6-12 under Johnson. ... The Clippers' 13 points in the first quarter were the fewest by a Phoenix opponent this season. The previous low was 14 by Sacramento on Dec. 12. ... A crowd of 19,455 was the Clippers' 10th consecutive sellout and 19th of the season. ... Los Angeles leads the season series 2-1, with one game remaining. ... The Clippers extended their franchise record of 13 consecutive games holding opponents under 100 points. They are 9-4 in that span.
